Adjusting for political climate.
September 26, President Trump announced his nomination of appellate judge Amy Coney Barrett. Major media outlets report a majority of senators will vote to confirm Trump's nominee.

According to the Senate website (https://www.senate.gov/legislative/nominations/SupremeCourtNominations1789present.htm), whenever a nomination is made, 73% of the nominees are confirmed and serve. In the last 50 years, 85% (11/13 - and the other two were withdrawn by the president) of nominees are confirmed when the same party controls the WH and the Senate. Thus, the question turns to timing in my mind. On average it takes 67 days (since 1975) to confirm a justice, which leaves plenty of time to accomplish the confirmation before the inauguration in Jan. For no confirmation to occur you would need for (a) Trump to not nominate anyone (he has already said he will do so quickly), (b) the Senate to refuse to vote (McConnell has already said they will vote), or (c) the Senate to deny a nominee. Thanks to a 2017 change, the Senate needs just 50 votes (not 60) to confirm a judge, which means Rep support is more than enough. Initially, I believed that pressure on key Senators who are up for re-election had a small chance at stopping a confirmation. I now realize this is wrong for several reasons. First, most of those seeking re-election have tied themselves to Trump in one way or another. It is also common knowledge that the GOPs base values SCOTUS appointees above almost any other issue. It is difficult to see how enough Republicans could be pressured in the correct way to reject or delay a vote in order to appeal to their base. However, and this is what I am now realizing and others have commented on as well, it doesn't actually matter whether we pressure Republican politicians during the election. Whether they are voted out or kept in, they will still have basically 2 months to ram a nominee through before the next cycle. The only reason I've left 9% on the No is that they technically have until January 20th to push through any lame duck policies if they need to, so it may come through after the 1st. Personally, however, I think it will come by late October, there will be a public outcry of hypocrisy and corruption, no one will do anything of substance, and we will live with the ramifications for decades to come.

On average, in the 229 year history of the Supreme Court, there have been 113 judges appointed, which means there is a turnover rate of approximately one judge every two years, so an appropriate historical anchor is around 50% probability each year, or around 20.8% in 5 months. For the 55 that have retired, the average age of retirement is 73.6 years. Of those on the court now, only two are older than this age (though they are in their 80s), RBG and Breyer. So I'd bump my prediction up around 5 points. With the health issues surrounding RBG, I'd give it another 5 points that a seat opens up, giving a 69% chance no seat becomes vacant before January 1st. Now, the average time between a nomination and confirmation in recent history is 67 days, or a little over 2 months, though in the current political climate it is possible the Senate will attempt to ram through a decision in less time given that McConnell has staked his career on the courts. Given that the Republicans will still be in control of the Senate on January 1st (regardless of the election) I'd give it 70/30 odds that a vacant seat is not filled by then.

Considering the age and health of the judges I estimate there is a 36 chance that a judge will vacate a seat for health or other reasons. Nominating a new judge on average takes 75 days and considering the national sentiment it might take a little longer. That is half the time left until January first and thus I think a 17% chance that a new judge will be confirmed before the new year.

Starting with the fact that since 1980, over the last 40 years, 13 replacements have occurred. That is 32.5% of the years. At the same time, the last 9 Justices have been confirmed from 1992 till 2019, that is 9 in the last 18 years, or one every two years, or 50%. I am therefore leaning towards 35-40% for the remainder of 2020.

Our base rate is 146 days. That’s the median time it took from the setting of the first public hearing by the Senate Judiciary Committee until confirmation. That equates to 4.86 months. [1] Let’s round that to 5 for simplicity. That means, if a justice were to die tomorrow and a replacement was immediately named, it would take until approximately December 11 to confirm a nominee. This rarely happens. Since 1975, it has taken the President an average of 20 days to announce a candidate to fill a Supreme Court vacancy which brings us neatly to December 31, 2020. [2] I think this safely eliminates the confirmation of a replacement before January 1, not to mention the dynamics of COVID-19 and an election year.

While one member of the Supreme Court has recently had health issues, that member has returned to the bench quickly after each illness or injury. It is currently July and it is unlikely that, barring a sudden death or incapacitation, that a member of the Court will leave so close to the start of the next term. Lastly, it is unlikely, given the uncertainty of the upcoming election, that a nomination or confirmation will occur in such a short period of time.

To answer this question, the probability of either death or motivation of each member must be assessed. RBG is the most likely candidate for vacating a seat and actuarial tables indicate less than 10% chance of death (other factors like her medical issues combined with the top of the line medical care I believe cancel each other out). This leaves only the probability of a motivation to resign by one of the conservative justices and only Clarence Thomas would be in a position to do that.
